<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/Written Submission of Women in Racing to Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee Inquiry into Women in Sport</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Women in Racing [WAS0044]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">This paper constitutes the written response of Women in Racing to the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee (‘the Committee’) Inquiry into Women in Sport (‘the Inquiry’). Women in Racing is happy to provide further evidence to the Committee as required.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women in Racing would like to see policy makers, including members of the Committee:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Expand Lord Davies’ report to apply the same targets to non-public companies and entities (for example within racing those could include the Horserace Betting Levy Board and the sport’s regulator, the British Horseracing Authority);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ask questions of Government and Ministers (including Secretary of State for Culture Media and Sport Maria Miller, Minister for Sport, Tourism and Equalities Helen Grant and Minister for Equalities Jo Swinson) about how senior appointments in public bodies are made in order to encourage a culture of transparency and openness and set a framework for monitoring the data; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Engage with leaders of public and non-public bodies and actively encourage diverse appointments by</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> honouring</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> those that comply and naming and shaming those that do not; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Celebrate the stories of women in racing, betting and other male dominated industries who make a difference.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About British Horseracing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">British racing contributes £3.45 billion annually to the UK economy and is the second most popular sport in the country with 5.58 million people going racing in 2012. It directly employs 17,400 people and has indirect and associate employment of over 85,000.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Women in Racing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women in Racing was founded in September 2009 with the vision to reach women across the industry in order to raise their profile and visibility in what is largely a very male dominated sport. On a tangible level, Women in Racing seeks to encourage senior female appointments in the various boardrooms that govern the sport and further help build the careers of those already in racing and related sectors, or those who may join it in the years ahead. Full information about the organisation can be found on the website at: </span><a href="http://www.womeninracing.co.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.womeninracing.co.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women in Racing is a not for profit organisation and has over 120</span><span style="color:#c00000; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">members obtained through word of mouth as all the management of the network is performed on a voluntary basis.  All members of Women in Racing must have a vested interest in the sport, either as owners or breeders or as employees working in a wide range of areas within the sport including racecourses, bloodstock, training yards and studs, management, media and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">communications.  Related industries such as betting, hospitality and events are also included.  In addition Women in Racing also has a dozen internationally recognised equestrian artists as members and has started to expand overseas.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Women in Racing’s Activities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women in Racing offers its members numerous tangible opportunities to further their career and integrate themselves into the industry, as well as for women-owned businesses to obtain new clients through informal networking.  These include, amongst others:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">‘On Track’ educational and networking events where keynote speakers are invited to discuss and engage in Q&amp;A within their area of expertise;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The first cross-industry mentoring programme where members can receive support and career guidance from senior members in order to further non-executive, corporate and entrepreneurial ambitions.  In addition to this is access to our corporate partner, Nolan Partners, which specialises in executive search within the sports and gaming industries; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">A grant programme which allows members to apply for a sum of up to £2,000 to help progress their career. This could be anything from a course or qualification which could aid promotion, to attendance at an event or financial support for a work experience opportunity.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Key metrics about Women in Racing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women are unrepresented at all levels of British racing’s management. The following list sets out the number of women within some of the key institutions at Executive and Board level:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Horserace Betting Levy Board (all DCMS appointments): 0/7 </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">British Horseracing Authority Board: 1/9 </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">British Horseracing Authority Executive: 1/5 </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Jockey Club Board: 1/8 </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Jockey Club Executive: 1/7 </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Arena Racing Company Board: 0</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Racehorse Owners’ Association Council: 3/15</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Thoroughbred Breeders’ Association Board: 0/12</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">National Trainers’ Federation Council: 4/20</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Professional Jockeys’ Association Council: 0/9</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Bookmakers’ Committee: 1/13</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The case for more Women in Racing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women in Racing’s central ambition of developing the role of women aims to benefit both working women but also crucially the sport itself which is continually financially challenged as well as having to deal with key issues such as integrity, horse welfare and maintain and growing its popularity. Given that numerous pieces of research</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> have emphatically shown that those with diverse boards and gender-balanced businesses at the senior executive level </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">perform better than their competitors and there is no reason to think that the British racing industry is any different. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">There is a growing understanding of the need to address the issue to ensure the management of British racing is as effective as possible and that it is reflective of racegoers and its wider fan base.  In recent months the issue has been debated within the racing media</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and in Westminster</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women in Racing remains committed to helping policymakers progress the debate on women and sport at all levels. Increasing women’s involved in the participation and management of sport has the tri-partite benefits of helping improve women’s lives, improve the world of sport, and raise the standard of British racing in particular.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:8.5pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Economic Impact of British Racing 2013, Deloitte, June 2013: </span><a href="http://www.britishhorseracing.presscentre.com/Press-Releases/Economic-Impact-of-British-Racing-2013-published-3e7.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.britishhorseracing.presscentre.com/Press-Releases/Economic-Impact-of-British-Racing-2013-published-3e7.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:8.5pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Various research pieces by McKinsey, Ernst &amp; Young, Catalyst, Credit Suisse, Heidrick and Struggles, Goldman Sachs and Lord Davies of Abersoch’s report of 2011 undertaken at the request of the Equalities and Human Rights Commission (2008) and its update in 2013.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:8.5pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Racing Post, Is Racing Sexist?, 3</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt"> October 2013. The article copied in Appendix of this paper.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 8.5pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Book Antiqua'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Women in Racing’s Chair Sally Rowley-Williams and Head of Policy Susannah Gill were invited to present to the All Party Parliamentary Groups of Betting and Gaming and Racing and Bloodstock on 29th October 2013.</span></p></bod